3 Variant level workflow
4 Variant Annotation and Visualisation and Exploration
4.1 Annotation
4.1.1 Variants will be annotated at cDNA change and protein change level using HGVS.
4.1.2 Where HGVS is ambiguous, this should be standardised against GeL standard

4.1.3 Annotate against GEL provided variant classifications (e.g. ACMG class) potentially including phenotype-genotype level information. Data can be accessed in bulk (e.g. nightly releases or live via API calls)
4.1.4 Annotate against GEL provided knowledge bases such as HGMD
4.1.5 Annotate SVs, CNVs and STRs
4.1.6 Annotate structural variation against external knowledgebases such as DGV and Decipher
4.1.7 Presentation of interpretedGenome variants is flexible to the inclusion of additional fields (‘columns’) of different types. (eg. prioritisation scores from other interpretation providers)
4.1.8 Annotations from tools predicting impact on splicing are displayed
4.1.9 Annotate variants against large-scale population data: EXaC, GNoMAD, 1000Genomes (including subpopulations), ClinVar
4.1.10 Annotations from >= 2 tools predicting variant impact or deleteriousness are displayed
4.1.11 Annotation of variants against other publicly available knowledgebases eg Decipher
4.1.12 Annotation of variants by user pre-specified groups of ‘favourite variants' status
4.2 Visualisation
4.2.1 Display basic quality metric for genotype calls (alternate allele frequency/total reads for each family member). This information will be available within the GEL supplied VCF as FORMAT fields
4.2.2 Display GEL variant allele frequencies as provided via GEL annotated VCFs, allele frequency releases to Tool providers or queries to GEL databases.
4.2.3 Display X, Y and MT chromosome zygosity appropriately. The Tool should be displaying the genotypes as provided and zygosity on haploid regions should occur at the level of GEL's calls.

4.2.4 Variants displayed with genotype and zygosity (as contained within the GEL supplied variant calls) clearly assigned to the relevant family member, with functionality for viewing zygosity across family members within the Tool

4.2.5 Additional GEL specified quality can be obtained from the Tool, for example on hovering over a variant or in a variant specific pane. Specifically, ability to display arbitrary INFO fields (at the family-variant level) and FORMAT fields (at the fami
4.2.6 Display variant annotations as per various annotations specified in (Annotation)
4.2.7 Display in a variant table of SVs, CNVs and STRs
4.2.8 Visualisation of CNVs/SVs/STRs in genome browswer including (i) genes involved (against all transcripts provided) and (ii) resolution of breakpoint to nucleotide level
4.2.9 Visual annotation and display in genome browser of CNVs/SVs/STRs using against tracts from knowledge-bases, e.g. DGV and Decipher.

4.2.10 GeL-specified tiered variant sets presented as three distinct tiers (1, 2 and 3), as per GeL-supplied data model/VCFs. Note: ReportEvents in the set of variants for presentation may have been derived from application of 1 or >1 gene panel ReportEve
Task.Notes:
MVEP - display tiered variants and identify each variant and its tier in each panel,
VP - more interesting functionality using the MOI, panel, etc.

Task.Name: 4.2.11 Visualise small variants in the context of large variants, for example to highlight that there is potentially a double hit event (CNV and SNV at same locus)
4.2.12 Other advanced quality/confidence metrics for variant calls (with clear and intuitive display or categorisation) are provided
4.2.13 Variants should be collapsed so that they are only be presented once, even if appearing in multiple analyses
4.3 Exploration

4.3.1 Filter variants against GEL provided allele frequencies. This annotation can be used for filtering against on a at least binned <=1%,<=2%,<=5%,<=10%,>10%. Multiple sets of allele and genotype frequencies can be released by GEL e.g. by ancestry, rare
4.3.2 Annotations from interpretedGenomes need to be available for filtering
4.3.3 Filtering of variants against GEL's tiers including information at the tier, panel, mode of inheritance and report event for small and large variants (and combinations there of)
